{{Infobox artwork/wikidata|year={{circa}} 1672}}
'''''The Guitar Player''''' is a circa 1672<ref name=uk/> painting by [[Jan Vermeer]], on display in [[Kenwood House]], [[London]] as part of the [[Edward Guinness, 1st Earl of Iveagh#Art collector|Iveagh Bequest]].  In 2012 Kenwood closed for renovations until autumn 2013, and the painting was on display in the [[National Gallery]] for this period, next to their own two Vermeers.<ref name=uk>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/paintings/johannes-vermeer-the-guitar-player |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-04-26 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130426073213/http://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/paintings/johannes-vermeer-the-guitar-player |archivedate=2013-04-26 |df= }}</ref> It was returned to Kenwood House in late December.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/dec/27/vermeer-guitar-player-art-kenwood-house |title=What Vermeer's guitar player taught me about the joy of art &#124; Simon Jenkins &#124; Opinion |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date= |accessdate=2017-07-15}}</ref>

On February 23, 1974, the painting was stolen from Kenwood House and held for a ransom of over $1 million (US) in food to be distributed on the Caribbean island of [[Grenada]], or else the painting would be destroyed by those who had stolen it.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120717151931/http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=oKdbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=sVENAAAAIBAJ&pg=809,5122199&dq=grenada+vermeer&hl=en ]</ref> Later, a small strip of the painting was sent to ''The Times'' of London along with a demand that the Irish Republican sisters [[Marian Price|Marian]] and [[Dolours Price]] be allowed to serve their prison sentences near their homes in Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.essentialvermeer.com/fakes_thefts_school_of_delft_lost_sp/vermeer_theft_02.html#.WTIEXBIrLHc |title=Vermeer Thefts: The Guitar Player |website=Essentialvermeer.com |date= |accessdate=2017-07-15}}</ref> It was recovered by [[Scotland Yard]] in the cemetery of [[St Bartholomew-the-Great]], in London's financial district, on May 7, 1974. Although the painting showed signs of dampness, it was otherwise undamaged.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120728163846/http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=VW5kAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Vn0NAAAAIBAJ&pg=1138,3283197&dq=vermeer&hl=en] </ref>

A period copy, ''[[A Lady Playing the Guitar]]'', is in the collection of the [[Philadelphia Museum of Art]].
